Author Name: **Christian Leber**
Original Redmine Message: 429 from https://www.veripool.org



---

Hello,

I want to simulate some middle sized design (as in the generated .cpp files are 120 MB in size), that has a pretty simple clocking scheme,
because it has only a single clk signal. (it uses: always @(posedge clk))

To interface the design my C++ code can i'm using the variables of the C++ object (as generated by verilator) directly.
(only the ones of the top level)

I set this signals /* verilator public_flat */


So I'm using a little function to progress to the next cycle:
```
void to_next_vlt_cycle(void) {
  for(uint32_t i=0;i<2;i++) {
     if(i == 0) Vtop->clk = 1;
     if(i == 1) Vtop->clk = 0;
     Vtop->eval();
     tfp->dump (main_time);
     main_time++;
  }
}

```
And in between calls to this function I'm reading and writing the variables of the top object.

Is that the right way to do it?

(as i understood the suggested way is using DPI, but I'm a bit unsure ATM what's the best way to connect it to my C++ code, because i want to instantiate multiple of the same verilated objects.)

My problem is that the design is not behaving as expected as in some signal is not propagated and I just want to know if I'm doing this completely wrong or not.


Regards

Christian Leber

